<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-333-906  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 333 906.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  April 10 1990 v4 n14 p31(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Storage Dimensions expands optical line. (MacinStor Write-OnceOptical, MacinStor Erasable Optical Subsystem) (productannouncement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Norr, Henry.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Storage Dimensions Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Storage Dimensions MacinStor Erasable Optical (Optical disk drive)(product introduction)Storage Dimensions MacinStor Write-Once Optical (Optical diskdrive) (product introduction)Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (equipment and supplies).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionOptical DisksDisk DrivesErasable Optical MemoryWORM.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Henry NorrandM;San Jose, Calif.andP;  -- Storage Dimensions Inc. has extended its line ofMacinStor optical storage devices in two directions, adding a fasterwrite-once optical drive and an erasable optical system that promisesnear-hard disk performance.andM;andgt;The new MacinStor Write-Once Optical drive stores 910 Mbytes on removable5.25-inch optical cartridges.andP;  The SCSI subsystem achieves data transferrates ranging as high as 655 Kbytes per second, according to the company.andM;The new WORM (write-once- read-many) drive is almost 300 percent faster and200 Mbytes bigger than its now-discontinued predecessor, the LaserStor.andP;  At$3,795, however, it is priced 21 percent lower.andP;  One cartridge is included;additional ones cost $160.andM;andgt;The MacinStor Erasable Optical Subsystem, which the company said is thefastest erasable optical system on the market, is now available at $7,995 fora single drive or $15,495 for a dual-drive unit.andM;The units are based on the Tahiti I mechanism developed by Maxoptix Corp., ajoint venture of Storage Dimensions' parent company, Maxtor Corp., and KubotaLtd. of Japan.andP;  The mechanism reads and writes two types of cartridges: theAmerican National Standards Institute-standard cartridges used by mostoptical drives based on Sony mechanisms and a proprietary type developed byMaxoptix.andP;  The former holds just under 600 Mbytes; the latter, using azone-bit recording technique, holds 1 Gbyte of data per cartridge.andM;While heavy optics on the read-write head slow down other erasable opticalsystems, the Maxoptix system moves some of the optics off the head, relyingon mirrors to relay data from the head to a non-moving part.andP;  The result,according to Storage Dimensions, is an average access time of 35milliseconds, or less than half that of the Sony technology.andP;  The driveoutperforms its competitors even when using ANSI-standard cartridges and doeseven better with the proprietary type, according to Storage Dimensions.andM;One 1-Gbyte cartridge is included with the single-drive unit and two with thedual-drive model.andP;  Additional 1-Gbyte cartridges are $395; the 600-Mbyte onesare $295.andM;The erasable system, announced last July (see MacWEEK, Aug.andP;  1, 1989) andoriginally scheduled for release in September, began shipping in limitedquantities in December but is now in full production, the company said.andM;Storage Dimensions Inc. is located at 2145 Hamilton Ave., San Jose, Calif.andO;95125; (408) 879-0300.andO;</TEXT></DOC>